One thing that Drew and I have learned over the years is how to handle conflict better. Just like other couples with small children and the demands of life, we come across bumps in the road. It's our job to navigate through them as a team. 

A phrase that I recently came across on @drmorgancutlip 's feed was framing a conversation with a statement: "The story I'm telling myself..."

Here's how I used it: I was getting really irritated every time I walked past the not yet unpacked bag of snow gear that Drew packed for our recent family vacation. Since I had packed everything for the kids aside from that bag - and then UNPACKED and did all the laundry - I was stumped as to why the packer of that one single bag couldn't unpack it. Truthfully, more than that, it was what the bag represented. 

I told Drew, "The story I'm telling myself when I see the bag of snow gear that is still unpacked is that you think ALL the boys' stuff is my job. I have already unpacked all their other stuff from the trip, done all their laundry, and put it away. Since you packed that bag and have passed it a ton of times without unpacking it, it feels like the message you're sending is 'this is all on you.' Is that accurate?"

Drew was quick to say, "No. Not at all. I'm sorry, that is not the message I intended." He then unpacked it. 

Now since this isn't my first caption like this I know what your knee jerk reaction might be: "Why do I have to tell him to unpack the bag?" I get it, I wish I didn't have to either.

But since I'm unwilling to live with resentment and planning to always live with Drew, I have to bring these issues forward. The phrase "The story I'm telling myself..." aids in lowering defensiveness and gives a peek into the mental/physical load that a lot of women experience.

Oftentimes, the stories we tell ourselves about our partners are inaccurate, but we cannot ever fact check them if we don't share them out loud.❤️

Let me know if this situation resonates or if you'll give this phrase a try! 

Xo. Ames

Our second child displayed a heavy parental preference. Add in two other children that had a lesser, but still noticeable preference for me…and I was under the crushing waves of motherhood.🌊

When the kids would make their preference known, “No! I want mommy to do it!!!!!” Oftentimes, I would just do it. Partially because I felt like I was choosing between a) just doing it quickly or b) a massive meltdown. 

We get into patterns, patterns that can be extremely hard to change.

Slowly, methodically…we started to make some changes. One of the great things about children is that they are very adaptable. I’ll never forget the night I bubbled over, I had a HECK of a bedtime (at the time I was putting everyone to sleep) and my husband was pleasantly tucked into bed, watching TV. I said, “Something has to change, I can’t do this anymore.”😤

Here are a few things we’ve done:
-Every other night bedtime routines. The boys know it’s a “mommy night” or “daddy night”. One of us does bedtime for the two older boys (they sleep in the same room) and one of us does it for our youngest. The boys have a dependable routine they can count on. Yes, it was a really hard 2 week transition for everyone. But it was absolutely worth going through that to get to the other side. 
-“No, I WANT MOMMY!!!!!!!!” I started to put my foot down with my partner and set boundaries for my children. Their dad is perfectly capable of wiping butts and getting drinks. Encouraging my partner, "You’re doing it, so don’t give in.” He’s been incredibly collaborative.
-I was (and still am) contributing to many of the issues. I get very overstimulated when a child is screaming for me or repetitively asking for something, so for a long time I’d rather do it than face a battle. This is my radical acceptance: I contributed to the patterns my family got into. AND, I still have to look in the mirror. Ex. When our kids ask for a refill on their drink, my husband will make them wait until it’s a good time for him. I might jump up and get it. Drew is willing to help, but he’s not willing to be their waiter…and our kids are at an age that I shouldn’t be okay being their waiter either.

Cheering for you.❤️
This week was looking so promising- we made it all the way to Friday.🫠

THIS. 

I wish I would've known this...

When it looked like everyone was having an easier time mothering than I was.

When my kids had a string of illnesses that made me feel like *we* were doing something wrong.

When I was so overwhelmed by having 3 children that I often found myself tearful.

When I felt like my partner and I were the only ones struggling with a child that had bigger reactions. 

Etc. etc. 

Parenting *IS* hard. There is not always a hack or a script, sometimes it just is. 
It's helpful to know that just because it's hard, doesn't mean you're doing it wrong.❤️

Xo. Ames
Merry Christmas from our family to yours. Love, The Kiefer Family ❤️🎄

Happy New Year.🥳✨

Party started at 5pm, should wrap up by 10.😂

How are you spending tonight? Sweatpants, house party, out?!✨

Reminder: Small progress IS progress.

I remember when we had our premarital counseling almost a decade ago…our scores for conflict resolution were NOT good. I’ll never forget when our mentors asked how our parents handled conflict because that has a big influence on how we ourselves learn to manage it. That was eye opening for both of us. 

I’d love to think our marriage mentors would be so proud of how far we’ve come by being open to learning and working on this part of our marriage. It's been a thousand little steps. Like the first time I didn't force Drew to stay awake and sort something out, rather trusted that space to reflect and sleep would help us. Or how he's gotten better at apologies, one at a time.❤️

Let me know which one of these examples is speaking to you.

Always cheering for you and yours, 
Ames

Never underestimate walking.✨
I took so many more this past year, and I didn't regret a single one of them.

I know that each day I can:
-Hydrate well.
-Walk.

Some days much more, but each day at least this.❤️

I aim for 10,000 steps a day- do you have a goal you try to hit????✨

I've been a mom for 6.5 years now, and I'm still learning constantly. Wouldn't it be the most beautiful thing if we gave ourselves the grace to learn?✨

At each stage and age, it's my child's FIRST time there and my first time as HIS mom at that stage. Each of my children are unique, so even if I've been through that age/stage with their older brother, this child will bring something new. 

Here's what's coming up for me now:
-Each of my children needs a different type of mothering. They are at their best when I'm treating them as individuals. This certainly has its challenges, especially when it comes to things like *time*. One requires more one-on-one attention, so navigating how to give that time while also meeting the needs of the other two can leave me feeling stretched thin. We just do the best that we CAN.❤️
-The internet doesn't always know what's best for me and my family. I LOVE experts as much as the next person, but it took me experiencing a high-reacting child to realize that the perfect script doesn't work for everyone. I'm done thinking I'm doing something wrong, rather I know life and parenthood have a beautiful array of nuances. Often, those are talked about much less, but you are NOT alone if you're in the same boat. 
-Taking care of myself is taking care of my family. I've learned what I need to make myself feel well, and now I *regularly* do those things. It's made such a difference in my mental health to do them (and not feel guilty)...I only wish I would've started sooner.

Let me know what you've learned over your motherhood journey. And hey, if you're new to the role...I hope what you get out of this is the idea of giving yourself grace ALL along the way. Allowing yourself to be new at each season.✨

Xo. Ames

Often the work of parenting is actually improving *ourselves*. I’ve had such a journey with my body as well as my relationship with food and exercise. 

This goal is SO important to me. And I know that what I’m modeling is what sinks into their minds as “normal”.

As I tried to point out, none of us will get this perfect. But, in my book, it matters that we’re mindful and trying. 

What else would you add?❤️👇🏽

I'll never forget when I was listening to Untamed and I heard this quote. It was so poignant- I pressed rewind and listened to it twice more- writing down the words. 

You see, when you have 3 boys...you hear ALL the gender stereotypes. Most I let roll of my back, but the one that irks me is when people imply that boys have less capacity to be kind and caring.

I don't believe it for a second- because I'm surrounded by kind, caring, and loving men. I've been lucky that way- to see my dad and husband be all of this and more.😭❤️ 

One of the greatest compliments we've received as parents is how kind our boys are. Our oldest's first grade teacher said, "He is kind to everyone. Truly one of those people that believes everyone should be included. His classmates all trust him." My eyes welled with tears as she spoke about him in this way.😭

Cheers to continuing to nurture kindness and caring that in ALL of our children.🙌🏽

May bedtime be in your favor tonight 🙏🏽

Cole will say anything and everything 🤪 Tell us what we missed 😂👇🏽

The invisible load of motherhood, let's talk about it:

Drew will often ask me, “where are the kids?”

Meanwhile, just by sound- I can tell exactly where each child is and can almost always tell you what each is doing. My brain is ON with an ear to the children, his brain is focused on  whatever is right in front of him.

This is the smallest glimpse into how a mother’s brain works. And what I’m hearing from this community of mothers- is at the very least, they just want acknowledgement. “I SEE how much you do AND how much thought and planning goes into it. I’m thankful for all you do for our family." In my dream scenario the partner would offer, “And I want to talk about how I can help to take some of this heavy stack off your plate."

Swipe through and see what speaks the loudest to you. The first step is often getting the unseen to be seen.❤️

Loved these 5 points from @psychedmommy 's invisible load blog post. 

I expanded on them below each of her points. I share my own personal experience of coming out from under the crushing waves of carrying too much- and asking my partner to take some things off my plate.❤️

I know that this isn't easy to tackle PLUS some people's partners aren't as amendable. That sucks- and I'm sorry to those that are experiencing someone that doesn't recognize that this is very real.❤️

I KNOW that a lot of couples CAN get to a better place with sharing the load- because it's something we've gone through. Things feel MUCH better now that we split the load of household and parenthood better.

For Drew and I, it has made our relationship BETTER because I'm no longer carrying around the extremely heavy feeling of resentment. I've got more capacity for our relationship.

Would love to hear how you've worked on shifting some of the load to your partner.✨

I've been very inspired to think, "would I be comfortable with my son expecting this same splitting of tasks from a partner?" If you have a girl, "Would I want her to carry the load I carry?" We know that what they SEE demonstrated is more important than anything we can say.❤️

-Ames

When I think back to when my children were babies, some of it is a blur.

Between the lack of sleep and high demand, I can't remember some of the details of that season. 

But I do have this one very vivid memory. We had just brought our 3rd baby Cole home and our oldest Max (who was 3 at the time) started to have a really hard time going to sleep. 

One particular night, I was trying to get Max to sleep while baby Cole was in my arms. The baby was hungry and I was trying my best to juggle both of their needs. I thought to myself, "I know this time goes so fast." As I stared down at Cole I also remember thinking, "I can't even imagine you at Max's age. I can't imagine you being 3...how will your voice sound? What interests will you have? What will you be like?"

And now, he is 3. 

This isn't one of those posts to say, "Enjoy every moment." Because I couldn't. At times parenting 3 little people was incredibly challenging.

This is a post to say there is some magic in every single season.💫 It doesn't leave as your children grow older, it just shows up in different spots.

I wish I could tell that mom having a hard time juggling those little ones that she WAS doing it by doing the best she could. Someday the role would be easier and she'd smile at the memory with happy tears for what was and what is.😭😭💕❤️

I LOVE both my roles: my role as a business owner and my role as a mother.

It has been SUCH a journey for me to be able to use the word LOVE when it comes to my career- because there was a good stretch where I felt an immense amount of working mom guilt. There were stretches where it felt more stressful than rewarding. There were times when I didn't know if our schedules were sustainable (lack of sick time and all the sicknesses that come with having young children). 

When I asked this community what the hardest parts of working motherhood are for them, here are the responses. 

Now, I feel much more sure-footed and I want to help other women coming behind me. First I thought it was important to acknowledge the challenges and see that you are NOT alone in them.❤️

What one speaks the loudest to you? What would you add?

#workingmom #workingmomlife #workingmomproblems

Tonight we sat down to dinner the 5 of us.

Everyone ate the food we served and happily stayed in their seat. We caught up on our days, laughed, guessed each other's favorite food, talked about the names we were thinking of naming each of them (they all liked their own names best).❤️

I soaked in how much everyone enjoyed the meal and the company. There was an ease to it, that hasn't been present in previous years. Sometimes in those years, there was more food on the floor than in their mouths, someone was always in my lap, there could be more crying than conversation.

This is not a post for you to wish away time if you're in the chaotic dinner season...

This is a post to say, there are things to look forward to. In each part of parenthood- we've got to find the specialness that is right in front of us. We can't always be reaching back for what was or worrying about what is to come-- but, BEING right there with the family we have today.❤️

One gift that comes with aging is perspective. Another is experience. 

I’ve enjoyed getting to know myself better. I’ve enjoyed being myself everywhere I go.

Let me know if any of these resonate with you.✨✨✨

Snaps from spring break.📸

BTS: spring break brought on a wave of mom guilt for me. I see so many of Max's friends or other families on Instagram taking these big trips, and that wasn't in the cards for us this year (our first big family trip is in June). 

With all the snow and sick days this year, Drew and I decided to try to strike a balance between giving the boys some exciting experiences and working a few days this week. I had to address the waves of mom guilt that came up with the choice of balance. 

I noticed the pressure I was putting on myself versus what my children were experiencing. 

Multiple times this week that boys have proclaimed, "This is the best day ever!". Even though we were right here in good old Wisconsin. 

Spending a night at a water park hotel, rock climbing, and exploring Cave of the Mounds are three experiences that are etched in my memory from my childhood-- so I had to remind myself that this was *enough*.

Comparison can be a thief if we let it be. I had to coach myself to be right where we are, together and happy.❤️

If you've been around for a while, you know I struggled pretty bad with working mom guilt. 

It was so hard for me to conceptualize how I was going to manage being a mother AND having a career. Both are demanding. Both take a lot of time and energy. Both feel pressure filled at times.

I had fears like, "Is Max going to know that I'm his mom?" "Are our bonds going to suffer?"

This caption could be a book, because there were a lot of steps to getting to a better place. I was telling my friend today, I wish I could've gotten a glimpse into the future when I had all those worries. I could've seen how well it worked out. To see our nowaday reality- one in which the kids are thriving- and I am too.✨

Because we don't get that opportunity, I wanted to write some mantras that have helped me along the way and still help me if I'm having a tough day.

Although my working mom guilt has been largely quelled, I still certainly have my moments...so it's always nice to have them in my back pocket. I hope you take what you need.❤️

Last night, I was putting Trey to bed. Trey is such an intuitive little guy- he always knows when he’s tired and wants to go to sleep. This affords us some special moments together because it’s earlier than his brothers. 

As I'm tucking him in and cuddling him, he says, "I’m so lucky to have you and dad as my parents.”😭

I don’t think people talk enough about how special it is when children can articulate their own experiences. 

When the boys were younger, we were pouring so much into them. And of course- we’re rewarded with heart melting cuddles. THAT is such a special season.

And so is THIS. 

When you can hear their voice, their thoughts, their love, and appreciation- it can make your heart swell. Sometimes the boys catch me when I least expect it. They’ll call out “Mom?!” for the 100th time that day, but instead of asking for something they’ll say, “I love you.”

There is a key difference between:
There must be something wrong with me because I can't keep up vs. I'm drowning- I need more support.

I think it's something that should be talked about more. 

This reflects my exact experience. I had put so much pressure on myself as a first time mom to be able to "do it all". And for a time, I felt able to. But eventually and with the addition of more children, the amount that was on my shoulders was impossible to carry. I had realized that I was complicit in the roles and patterns that my husband and I got into. While he was largely able to feel himself and continue the things he enjoyed, I had been swallowed up by motherhood. 

I needed more support. More support from him. More support from our village (for us- our families, but also friends that are now as close as family). 

There wasn't something wrong with me, there WAS something wrong with my (and society's) expectations for mothers. I had to expect more help from my partner- who was absolutely willing to make sure that we cared for this family together so that we could both stay afloat.

If a mother is exhausted, I have a hunch it is because her load is too heavy to carry. She needs more support.❤️

Ps. As I've always told @molly.millwood.phd - I'm her biggest fan. She has two awesome episodes on the @herselfpodcast if you want to hear more from her!

Today is a very exciting day: the national championship game.🏀

Exciting for a couple reasons: 
-1. You may or may not know that basketball was the first love of my life. I was obsessed with playing the game- through high school. I love watching basketball.
-2. My husband's March Madness viewing obsession runs so deep that March can get a little contentious. This is the light at the end of the tunnel.

Figuring out how to support your partner's hobbies and interests can get really challenging during parenthood. He's been the "take off of work- don't miss a game" viewer ever since we started dating, but when we had kids...it hit different.

We're both very supportive of each other having a life outside the house and family. But here's what I've learned:
-I've got to speak up when my demand gets too high. Yes I want to support his things, but not the expense of burning myself out. As I've said before, I'm not going to sink so he can live HIS best life.
-Get proactive in finding time as a couple. We went on two dates this month (which is higher than average for us). Sure, one included basketball- but I know we do better if we get some time just the two of us. I want both of us to prioritize our marriage.❤️
-Take time to myself. Whether it's getting a workout in, going to book club, doing dinner with friends...making sure my cup is filled up helps me support him AND helps me feel my best.✨

Your partner's busy season might look different from mine (hello hunting), but  hopefully our experience can help yours go smoother.❤️

MM and basketball photo dump.😍🏀

One might say, we're not being set up for success.😩

Because change likely isn't going to happen quickly enough for our generation of working mothers- sometimes we need to modify as best we can.

How could you get a little further from the edge of your bandwidth? What could you put down?✨

For a long time, it felt like I had no margin in parenting. 

We have 3 children- and for many years, it felt like I was just getting by. So much of the time- I had to be INSIDE the moment. Because someone wanted to be held, or maybe they fell, or needed something from me. 

Tonight, I watched my 3 boys play outside for hours. I glanced every once and a while- and I always saw them having joy filled play. I almost started crying happy tears- because now I get to SEE the moments, be on the outside instead of under them. I'm not as demanded. I have more time to do things that I couldn't before. 

I never write a caption like this so that people will wish the time away. We had beautiful moments when our kids were younger, too. It's just different now. And I love sharing that different doesn't mean less special, it just means the specialness changes. Like a child telling you how thankful they are for you- that you're the bestest mommy. Or the sweet sentence they write in first grade about how they would share the pot of gold with their friends. Or the hug they gave their friend when the school day was done- because they wanted to squeeze them goodbye.❤️

Whatever season you're in, I hope you can feel some of the specialness of it.✨
Instead of only focusing on the moments you wish you would've done better, you also have to SEE all that you are doing well.❤️ None of us will get it perfectly, but the good news is: good is enough.

Do you want your daughter, niece, future daughter-in-law, next generation of women to feel the way that you feel inside of your role as a mother?

If not, what would you want to be different for them?

Of course, there are some HUGE societal factors involved in this conversation. And I would never downplay those, but I also believe that there is a lot of power in what we are demonstrating inside our own households. 

I'm raising 3 boys, but I'm still SO passionate about this subject because I want them to go into the world believing that a woman's joy, stress levels, and happiness are just as important as a male's. If I demonstrate that dad's hobbies and interests are prioritized, while mom always sacrifices...I'm not moving us forward.

I want the boys to see that mothers get time choice to do the things they love. I want them to see that mothers expect and accept support. I want them to see that I'm going to allow myself to finish my dinner before I jump up to attend to their every need. I want them to see that a mother takes time to take care of herself. I want them to see a mother who enjoys her work outside of the house- one who inspired them to find what fulfills them.

What you want to demonstrate might look similar or completely different- but it's worth thinking about.❤️

This quote is from @drbeckyatgoodinside from @herselfpodcast episode 146.🎧

Different seasons of parenthood have brought different challenges into Drew and I's relationship.

Right now, we have 3 energetic and talkative boys. 

We LOVE hearing what they have to say and their unique personalities bring us a ton of joy. 

AND it's hard for Drew and I to get a word in. We still *try* to do a quick catchup and connection when I come in the door with our crew, but we never get far. It's often interrupted by someone who really wants to tell us something or someone else who really wants us to watch him do something. I thought this photo of Cole depicted our current season well. 

I don't hear people talk enough about how the different seasons of parenthood present different challenges for the relationship of the parents. It's NOT easy to stay connected and everything isn't solved with having a date night every once and a while. 

This is a challenge and we don't have all the answers...but, I thought we'd share a few things we've found helpful:
-Most nights we go to bed at the same time. We have the opportunity to connect and cuddle when it's just the two of us. 
-We send kind text messages to each other throughout the day. We want to make sure our communication isn't just about the kids or transactional, but for US.❤️
-We try to eat lunch together every so often. It's something that we can fit into our schedules without having to get a sitter, and again...it's just the two of us. 

In what easy ways have you connected in your current parenting/relationship season?

This really got me thinking.

So often my friends and I will say things like, "I don't know why I'm so overwhelmed." "I don't know why I'm crying." "I don't know why I have no patience."

But the truth is, there is usually a multitude of reasons. And letting yourself realize all the things you're *new* at or all the things on your plate is a helpful exercise.

I hope that these reframes help you be kind to yourself.❤️

@lizandmollie gave the reframes! She'll be on @herselfpodcast soon!

Happy, happy birthday to one of my favorite people on the planet.❤️ I'll never stop being thankful that you entered my life and I can't stop thinking about everything we've been through together. The highs, the lows, and everything in between. Our friendship is one of the highlights of my whole life. Thank you for being caring, generous, hilarious, slightly demanding on the work front (lol), and just all around for being you.❤️

Setting a good example for your kids can look a lot of different ways.🙌🏽

For me, it includes showing them an example of someone that can set healthy boundaries and take care of herself. A person that has a self, which includes interest and passions outside of our home and family.

Motherhood, undoubtedly, changes us. It changes us in a huge way. I love being a mom to my 3 sons. AND, I still enjoy being Amy

The challenge that many of us face is finding a balance- and the thing is, it looks different in different seasons. It also will look different than your mom's, your sister's, your best friend's, your coworker's, etc.

Do you feel like you still have a self? What are things you do to feel like the YOU outside of motherhood? Would love to hear below.❤️

I love this photo. It's a snap of people that mean the world to me. A picture that I think we're all going to feel lucky to have, one that we can look back on.🥰

Often, I'm snapping photos here and there because I know we're going to cherish them. Even when our outfits don't match, and we're doing everyday things.

Trey (and the rest of his brothers) have such a special relationship with their grandparents. It meant the world to him that they were able to come to his soccer scrimmage. And my mother-in-law commented on how special it is to feel the boys' love for them- it's so strong.😭❤️

Of course as we near Mother's Day, many of us will recognize that we don't very often make it into the photos because we're taking them. This one, I was so happy to take. 

So two reminders: don't forget to snap photos of the people that you love so much. You'll cherish them- now and in the future. AND don't forget to remind your partner, friends, parents, whomever... to help get a few photos of you with your children. Even if you don't think you want to be in them, I think you'll look back at them someday with more tenderness in your eyes. Remembering a time when your children were so little- and you were happy in love even if you can see a trace of all the effort it takes to care for them.❤️

Couples with small children inevitably run into the dilemma of how they will spend their time. When the couple introduces children into their relationship, there is a recalibration that needs to happen to balance the demands of parenthood. This will impact both parents’ time for themselves.

This is an area where we've had to find our footing and figure out what feels good to BOTH of us. 

In the beginning, it was a lot of me saying yes because I felt bad saying no. Coupled that with heavy mom guilt and not doing much for myself and we had some really rough patches of resentment. 

I spoke with @eliweinstein_lcsw about this and really enjoyed his lens as a "dude therapist". Plus, I've added my thoughts. 

Is this something you and your partner have struggled with? Anything you've found to help? For me, it was working on saying no when I meant no...and saying yes to more things for me. Always appreciate the conversation.

-Amy

9 years later.❤️

Still celebrating our love all day, just in more casual clothes.☺️ I feel so thankful for this life we have together. It feels like we've spent 9 years growing and deepening our roots. Our love feels steady and strong.

Happy anniversary @bigdaddykiefer - here is to many more.🥂❤️

The overwhelm of modern motherhood.

If you're feeling overwhelmed, you aren't alone. This topic matters to me- as it's something that I've been tackling in my own life over the past couple years. I thought I could shed some light on how it shows up for me- because I know so many women out there can relate.

I'm told I'm "lucky" to have Drew. And I am. He is an amazing man and a hands-on dad. Still, it was really important to me to strive for a more balanced sharing of the load. We've come so far.✨

It's not just a "you" problem if you’re feeling overwhelmed. In many ways, we need better support and more of it. 

In this, I share the areas that Drew and I are still working on, as well as the areas that we've grown in. Hoping this helps provide some insight. Xo. Ames

There is an older couple that lives across the street from us. Often in the evening, they'll be outside in their rocking chairs.
While they are having a quiet evening, we'll be outside chasing around our 3 wild boys.

If ever we make eye contact, they are *never* annoyed with our chaos. Instead, there is a knowing gaze. Their children are adults now. But, I can see that they remember this phase. They'll watch our boys run around, pretend they don't hear when I raise my voice, and always give the friendliest hello.🥺

It is grounding for me to think that one day this will be a distant memory. Drew and I will be rocking side by side and remembering the years in which we were almost losing our minds, but also had the most adorable and loving little humans around. Years when our hands were as full as our hearts.

“You're gonna miss this
You're gonna want this back
You're gonna wish these days hadn't gone by so fast”

I'm taking a good look around tonight, counting my blessings, and trying my very best to also leave some patience for that man I want to stay with and rock by.😭❤️

I simultaneously can't believe that we've been married for 9 years AND it feels like we've done so much more life together at this point. 

There are a million reasons I'm lucky to be married to Drew, but one of my favorite things is that we've both grown and evolved over time. We've given each other the space to do so, while still making sure that the roots of our relationships are strong and steady.

Right now, one of my biggest mothering challenges is how demanded I feel. Someone always needs something, or wants you to watch them do something, or wants you to be with them. 

I'll never forget when my therapist said to me, "This is a SEASON Amy. Yes, it feels overwhelming because IT IS. But this also won't last forever. Someday, you won't be their go to person...".

I burst into tears and she quickly replied, "Whoops, that was supposed to be helpful."

Sending you the biggest mamahood hug today- whether you’re having a day that makes you cry happy OR overwhelmed tears...they have exactly who they need.❤️

When Drew and I became parents, I slowly came to the realization that my relationship was NOT as progressive as I thought it was.

When we had our first son I, like many women, happily took on a lot of the kid related duties. When we added another little one…my load felt so heavy.😩 I couldn't carry it well and I certainly couldn't be the partner that I wanted to be...because I felt so resentful.

Drew and I starting to share the load more equally has been a journey of 1,000 steps, 10 books, therapy sessions, etc. You know when our teachers used to say, "Show your work!"- I want to do so in this caption because it's much too flippant to think people that were socialized in a certain way and fell into some unbalanced habits can just change quickly.

I do want you to know that sharing the load more equally has ENHANCED our relationship. I think people think a partner might resent having to do more, but that’s not always the case. Sharing the load has created a more happy and steady relationship, which has helped immensely during this demanding season of raising 3 little boys.

I'd love to know- which of the loads feels heaviest to you?

Xo. @ameskiefer ❤️

Three boy joy.✨✨✨

Recently, I’ve been receiving lots of messages from women that have just found out they’ll be adding a 3rd boy or they just birthed their third boy. Their messages tell me that our family has helped her to wrap her mind around the news in a positive way. 

When you are one sex and have 3 children of the opposite sex, you are the one that tends to get *a lot* of unsolicited comments. They can be from perfect strangers and they can be from people that are really close to you. 

“Are you still going to try for a girl?” “3 boys?! Boys just won’t care for you when you're older like girls will.” “3 boys? Your husband must be so happy.” 

While those comments used to really annoy me, I now have a different headspace about them. Often, that comes with time and experience.

These commenters don’t see the absolute joy that our children bring us. They don’t feel the happiness that we feel inside of our home. They can’t feel the completeness that we feel, knowing that no one is missing- we have everyone right here. 

I think things tend to bother you less when you no longer feel defensive- and that’s where I’m at. People cannot take your joy and contentment away from you- you just have to realize you don’t need to convince them of it. Maybe they’ll never understand, and that’s okay.💙

We hope we can help you to see what a hoot and a blessing this life is (just as I would’ve felt with either sex).

Things we learned about going on a largely sun/beach vacation with 3 kids:
-Allegedly spray sunscreen "stings". They much preferred the lotion sunscreen.
-Bucket hats advised! We were constantly putting sunscreen on them and they had baseball hats on most of the time, but I wish we would've had bucket hats to protect their necks.
-Long sleeve SPF shirts strongly advised. Again, there was just SO much sun there- it really helped to have their top halves covered most of the time. Consider having long sleeves with hoods.
-Good goggles are a must! Splashing x salt water do not mix well- make sure you pack goggles. And they will say, "Mom, where are my goggles?!" no less than 100x. I would bring spare pairs!
-Good swimsuits. The built in compression shorts were king on this vacation. No chaffing or soreness. If you have girls, I'd get the long sleeve suits.
-Allow for sun breaks. We did let our kids get a little tablet time after water and before dinner. Just a little downtime was super helpful in transitions.
-Snacks are king. Take more snacks than you'd think! It helps especially if the kids are trying new foods- always good to have back up.
-Finding "treasure" (seashells, rocks, etc) can entertain them for long periods! The boys and their friends got so into it.

The marriage reminded I needed to hear 👇🏽

One of my favorite parts of my job is getting to interview people. Today, I talked to Dr. John Van Epp, a renowned marriage and relationship expert. 

At the end of the interview he said something that really stuck with me. He said one of the keys to his marriage (44 years and counting) is that they have a respect and admiration for each other. 

He admires the things in his wife that he isn't good at, and vice versa. They really see how having two different people with two different strengths and personalities is valuable and enriching to their relationship and lives. 

After the interview, I reflected back to him that those of us that are in partnership with small kids...can fall into seeing the differences as annoyances. 

Here's what I mean: 
When we were dating, it was easy to look past some of the quirks and habits that our partners had. Maybe we even found them endearing. Then all of the sudden, you're 2 kids in, under the load of responsibilities and you want to roast your partners little potatoes for the habits that they have *always* had. 

Marriage is give and take, we all know that. But, when we're stressed we all of the sudden want our partner to have a personality transplant. To see things the way we see things. To do as we do. To care more about what we care about and less about what we don't.

Today, Dr. Van Epp reminded me to remember to see the differences as enriching and helpful. Lord knows I'm never going to be an awesome planner, meticulous in checking all of our accounts, keeper of a (could be) award winning suburban lawn, rememberer of all special occasions, grill master, or slow and methodical person. Drew is all these things and so much more. 

There are so many positive qualities that each of us bring into our relationship, I just have to remember to *look* for those in this full season. I hope he is also looking for my positive qualities.♥️

I'll never forget when I was chatting with my therapist during a really tough time in my parenting journey. We were talking about letting myself feel all the feels that come with life. She said a few phrases that really resonated- "How do people appreciate the sun if they never see rain?" "How do you know joy without sadness?"

So many of us have been taught to run away from negative feelings- but she reminded me that it is an inevitable part of life. Tears, time, and talking- that's the way through she told me. 

When I shared this the first time a few years ago, I had mentioned at the end of the caption that one day soon I was hoping for less clouds. 

It isn't that I have an easy parenting life now, but things have shifted for us. No longer is my body demanded in the way it once was, no longer am I up multiple times a night trying to help a little person get through their night, the tantrums have spread out, the children can get their own drinks and snacks, we're not only out of diapers but almost everyone can even wipe their own little tush, we can make it through most dinners as a family. 

If you're in the season where there feels like more hard moments than enjoyable ones, know that those clouds will pass. You'll be out from under mothering and able to find even more enjoyment in those little ones you're working so hard to raise. 

All of that to say, your kids growing up isn't all sad. It's what they're supposed to do, and we're the lucky ones that get to appreciate the sun more.

This morning, I looked at all the dishes in the sink and the filled countertop. It isn't exactly an unfamiliar sight, but also not one that I enjoy. 

I glanced at the clock and had to make the decision that I had better continue down the path of leaving for work and leave the kitchen for later. 

It's tough to live in an undone state.

I could spend every minute of my day doing something- and the truth is I might still be behind on all the things that this phase of life takes. Even with a partner that contributes. 

Over the past couple of years, I've learned to be gentler with myself.

This morning it sounded like, "I know you want to get that kitchen in a better spot right now, but you also know you have to send that presentation off today. This will have to wait, that needs to be the priority."

Being reasonable and rational with myself instead of saying things like, "We can never keep up" "I'm such a mess." "I can't keep up with anything" or whatever else one might say to themselves...has been incredibly helpful. 

What if instead of thinking it's a personal flaw that we can't keep up, we start realizing that too much is expected of us? 

There will come a day when the dishes aren't behind and the school projects of the day aren't spread out on the kitchen counter, but I know I'm going to miss this beautifully chaotic time. So I try my best to enjoy this undone season and be a little gentler with myself along the way.♥️

Tell me if this sounds familiar:

Your partner has less patience than you’d like for your kids…and in turn, you have less patience for your partner.😅😤😩

This is one of the things that I spoke to my therapist about, since it seemed like Drew and I were really stuck in a cycle. To be honest, this *still* definitely ranks up there as one of our most common squabbles…but, she did help me recognize a few things.

1) ALSO see Drew’s parenting strengths. I was so honed in on the place where he fell short, that it was in BOLD. Now, I try to take a step back and remember all the places where he is strong as a parent: he’ll play outside for as long as the kids want to, he is affectionate and makes his love for them known, he coaches their teams and prioritizes being at their activities, etc. etc. She reminded me that we all have seasons that our personalities and skill sets will be better suited for. 
2) My therapist Kristin also reminded me that we’re different people and it’s okay to have different parenting strategies. She reminded me that at the end of the day, our kids are in a safe and loving home, which is the most important thing. I was expecting that Drew take the exact same approach as me- which was putting too much stress on both of us. 
3) Try to have some grace. At the end of the day, Drew and I are teammates. So trying to see things as US versus the issue instead of me versus Drew was important. Drew’s overstimulation and response to noise is more sensitive than mine- I can easily see that. Of course I can’t shoulder everything to appease this, but are there times where I have the capacity to help when he’s in that state? Yes.

When I posted about this in my stories, SO MANY people replied that this is common in their relationship too. Just know that you aren’t alone…and I’m sure if you look to see some strengths in your partner's parenting, you can probably find them too.♥️ None of us are perfect, and we don't have to be to be good parents.

Ps. Drew approved this message to be shared. He’ll always be more important to me than anything I do here, and I love that he loves the mission of sharing our tougher spots to help other couples.

The demands of the little kids years on a marriage are HIGH. Here are a few things we've learned over the last 7 years with 3 kids:

-Learn to fight fast. If Drew and I have an argument, we need to be able to figure it out and get back on the same page. Sometimes that's letting something go, sometimes that's an apology. We need each other and feel like we've grown in this area during our most demanding years.
-If you're feeling resentful- it's better to speak up and work together to make a change. Believe me, I've tried the "I'll just do it" approach or saying yes when I really meant no...and it was a tough season for our marriage. We've both learned, we'd rather each person speak up for what they need so we could stay away from resentment. If your partner isn't being themselves anymore, maybe it's because they need more help.♥️
-Remember what you enjoy as a couple and try to make some time for it. Drew and I were friends first and we love spending time together/have a fun/joking element in our relationship. During our harder seasons, we lost a bit of that lightheartedness. I'm so glad we've made room for it to come back into our relationship.
-Share the load. This will look different for EVERY couple, but the best thing that happened to us was figuring out how to shift more tasks to Drew. We check in with each other to make sure we're BOTH staying afloat. I was sinking before so that Drew wasn't as inconvenienced, but that really didn't help our relationship. Now that our load feels more equitable, we're happier as a couple.

Hang in there if you're in a tougher stretch, we've certainly been there.♥️ Which one speaks loudest to you or what would you add?

When our children were younger, it was so hard to imagine the upcoming phases. We were in survival mode, under the needs of 3 little kids. 

I know my children are still relatively young, but they are getting to ages that I couldn't have imagined in that season. Our middle just turned 6- and I could hardly believe it. My dad quipped, "How do you think I feel about you being 37?"

Each phase has had incredible things about it and challenging things about it- this time is no different. 

But, I do want to continue to shed light on the good that is to come if you're coming behind me. Knowing that there are things to look forward to. I know a lot of people have a hard time with their children growing up AND it's a beautiful thing to witness, there are bright, bright spots.💫

A few of my favorite things: 
-Their personalities shine through. The uniqueness of each and every person (if held lovingly) continues to show. I love getting to know each child, at every age and stage. 
-The independence. We have 2 kids that get themselves all the way dressed in the morning. Again, something I could've hardly imagined just a couple years ago. 
-Sitting down to dinner. I love that we can all sit down together around the table. We each share about our days- it's become a treasured part of my day. 
-Sharing similar interests. Hiking, football, going on walks, coloring, tubing, boating, Badger games, etc. etc. etc. We have more overlapping interests and the kids are getting to ages where they can now SIT THROUGH a whole game and enjoy it *with us*. 

I remind myself to not rush through life and always look around to make sure I'm experiencing the joy of the season.♥️

#momlife #motherhood #momof3 #momsgetreal #madisonmom

A positive note on sharing the load of parenting.🤍

Drew is on a work trip right now (only has a couple a year)- and I miss him and his help so much.

Like many couples with kids, it was a journey to find out how to balance all the demands that come with having a family. We used to have a "state of the union" meeting every Sunday as we worked to figure it out (read: we had a lot of work to do). I was often feeling overwhelmed and like I was just keeping my head above water.

We worked together to figure out how to share the load more evenly so I didn't have to feel like that. We've worked to split things according to our strengths and have a system that works for BOTH of us. When he's gone, I notice all the things he does for the house and the boys and it makes me appreciate how far we've come.♥️

If you're hoping to get to a better place- things that helped us:
-Meeting each Sunday- we'd talk about how we were both FEELING. Often, being overwhelmed/over demanded can lead to anger and resentment. If someone is feeling this way, they likely need more help/more sharing of the load.
-Read @everodsky 's Fair Play and @tdufu 's Drop the Ball. I've learned so much from both of these women. 
-Realize that different seasons need different recalibrations. Maybe something that used to work just doesn't anymore. It's okay to need a change in roles.
-Think long game. Of course change is hard and someone having to pick up more tasks has challenges- but our relationship is better for it. Both of us feeling like ourselves helps our marriage.

Xo. Amy
